Hello from Cleveland! (It’s a bit cold outside).
Great visit to the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio, with the kids.

Proud son moment!

My mom, Rosie Castro, has expressed interest in being appointed by the city council to fill Ana’s unexpired term (and not running for election in May). It won’t come as a surprise that I am thrilled. I believe she’d do an excellent job! She has a passion for public service, she knows the issues our neighborhoods and our city face very well, and she has tremendous integrity. 

My mom ran for city council in 1971, when she was just 23 years old. She ran at a time when women and people of color could hardly ever get elected in our city. Instead of giving up on a dream, she dedicated her life to bringing about progress so that others could break barriers that she and her generation had begun to knock down. 

I believe it’s fitting that, 52 years after first running, she may get a chance to serve on city council at last, even if only for just a brief few months until someone new is elected this May and takes office on June 1. It speaks of change and of our continued hope for progress.

social_posts.post_text:
I’m so proud of my mom! She first ran for the San Antonio City Council in 1971 at the age of 23. She didn’t win—almost no women or people of color did back then—but she spent her career breaking down barriers and helping to open doors for others to walk through, including me and my brother @joaquincastrotx. Today she was appointed to fill a vacancy in City Council District 7. Congratulations, at last, Councilwoman Rosie Castro! 
Full circle and then some.
Proud to join amazing leaders in Selma today who are working to protect civil rights and advance equality in our country.
Hello from Montgomery! Can’t come to Alabama without getting some good barbecue at @dreamlandbbq .
Tune in on Saturday and Sunday at 8 pm ET/7 pm CT!
Enjoyed guest hosting for @aymanm on MSNBC tonight! Tune in again tomorrow at 8 pm ET. (Thanks to @aliciamenendezxo for the photo!)
Grabbing a slice… or six!
Happy Birthday to my Baby Girl, Carina! 14 years old today! Where has the time gone? Carina is sweet, caring, super smart, and she makes me proud to be her dad every day.
Spring break in NYC. I feel like a dinosaur perusing the counters at Glossier with Carina, Cristián and a sea of teens.

Had a blast today visiting the @columbia campus, including a stop at Wallach Hall, where I lived while working as a legal assistant in NYC during the summer after college graduation. We also made it to @themuseumofmodernart this afternoon!

Hello from DC! Today we toured the Capitol (an actual tour, not a riot), dropped by @joaquincastrotx ‘s office (where I got to thank his staff for their great work—and take over his office for a few minutes!), and went by the Oyster Bilingual School (which Carina attended a few years back).
Today in Washington!

Happy Birthday to my amazing mom!
To all the wonderful moms out there and especially to my mom, Rosie, wishing you a Happy Mother’s Day!
Chicago!
I’m so proud of Carina and Cristián! Carina is wrapping up 8th grade and Cristián’s finishing 2nd. Feeling blessed to be their dad.
West Side SA. Soul of the city.

Next week will mark the end of my mother’s tenure as Councilwoman for San Antonio’s District 7. She has worked for so long to open up the doors of opportunity to others. Her public service these last three months has been just one more example of her commitment to lifting up her community. She has served with integrity, been a truth-teller, and has set a wonderful example for me and so many more.
These two make life funny, exciting, joyful and occasionally heartburn-inducing. Happy Father’s Day to my dad and to all the amazing dads out there!
Beautiful night in NYC!

Enjoyed a conversation with a fantastic group of civic leaders from across the country who are part of the Young American Leaders Program, moderated by former SBA Administrator Karen Mills, at @harvardhbs on Thursday.
A slow Sunday, thankfully.

“How many people have to die? How many kids have to die before people that yeah, they want more border security, but they say this is not who we are.” @juliancastrotx

Took the kids to watch @bluebeetle last night and watched it again tonight with my mom. Great movie! It’s got plenty of the usual superhero action and it’s also funny, has a lot of heart, reflects Latino culture superbly, and is political in a smart way. Worth watching!
You’re invited! (Joaquin’s getting old!)

I came anyway…and brought him a Happy Meal, just to punctuate the fact that he’s still my baby and it’s too soon to get embarrassed. Teenagerhood is starting way early for this one—he’s only a third-grader!

Dear Friends,
 
Exciting news! On January 1, I will become the new CEO of @latinocommfdn , the nation’s largest Latino-serving foundation. Under the leadership of current CEO Jacqueline Martinez Garcel, California-based LCF has raised more than $100 million to build Latino civic, political and economic power. In just a few short years, it has established the largest network of Latino philanthropists, mobilized Latinos to vote, and invested substantially in Latino entrepreneurship and the well-being of Latino youth and families throughout the state. I look forward to deepening LCF’s impact in California and to expanding it into Latino communities nationwide.
 
LCF’s work has never been more urgent. Today, one in four of our nation’s children are Latino—and nearly one in five Americans overall. That means our nation’s destiny is intertwined with the destiny of the Latino community like never before. By investing in Latino success, we can ensure a brighter future for all.
 
I will remain based in San Antonio and look forward to commuting to California to work closely with LCF’s amazing team. Like so many of you, I feel blessed to have had tremendous opportunities in life, and I want to continue making that kind of opportunity possible for others. LCF does that every single day. My heart is full as I begin this journey.
 
Thank you for your friendship and support.
 
Julián
 
Learn more about the Latino Community Foundation and today’s announcement at latinocf.org
